{"title_page": "Shekhawati language", "text_new": "{{Infobox language\n|name=Shekhawati\n|nativename=\u0936\u0947\u0916\u093e\u0935\u093e\u091f\u0940\n|states=[[India]] ([[Shekhawati]] region of [[Rajasthan]])\n|speakers= 3 million \n|date=2002\n|ref=e18\n|speakers2=Census results conflate some speakers with Hindi.\n|familycolor=Indo-European\n|fam2=[[Indo-Iranian languages|Indo-Iranian]]\n|fam3=[[Indo-Aryan languages|Indo-Aryan]]\n|fam4=[[Western Indo-Aryan languages|Western]]\n|fam5=Rajasthani\u2013Marwari\n|fam6=[[Marwari language|Marwari]]\n|iso3=swv\n|glotto=shek1243\n|glottorefname=Shekhawati\n}}\n\n'''Shekhawati''' is a [[Rajasthani language]] of [[Indo-Aryan languages]] family and is spoken by about three million speakers in [[Churu district|Churu]], [[Jhunjhunu]] and [[Sikar]] [[districts of Rajasthan]].<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20160303194604/http://www.sumania.com/lang/allindi10.html Shekhawati]</ref> Though a very important dialect from the grammatical and literary points of view, yet very little work is carried out on it. \nIn 2001 A [[descriptive grammar]] of Shekhawati has been published. Shekhawati, like [[Bagri language|Bagri]] dialect of [[Ganganagar]] and [[Hanumangarh]] districts, has [[parallel lexicon]] which make it very rich from the [[lexicographical]] point of view. [[Word order]] is typical [[Subject\u2013object\u2013verb|SOV]] and there is existence of [[implosives]]. Beside presence of [[high tone]] at [[suprasegmental]] level classify it with other [[dialects of Rajasthani]]. It has contributed a lot to the development of Rajasthani language and [[linguistics]].\n\n==References==\n\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Languages of Rajasthan]]\n\n\n{{IndoAryan-lang-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox language\n|name=Shekhawati\n|nativename=\u0936\u0947\u0916\u093e\u0935\u093e\u091f\u0940\n|states=[[India]] ([[Shekhawati]] region of [[Rajasthan]])\n|speakers= 3 million \n|date=2002\n|ref=e18\n|speakers2=Census results conflate some speakers with Hindi.\n|familycolor=Indo-European\n|fam2=[[Indo-Iranian languages|Indo-Iranian]]\n|fam3=[[Indo-Aryan languages|Indo-Aryan]]\n|fam4=[[Western Indo-Aryan languages|Western]]\n|fam5=Rajasthani\u2013Marwari\n|fam6=[[Marwari language|Marwari]]\n|iso3=swv\n|glotto=shek1243\n|glottorefname=Shekhawati\n}}\n\n'''Shekhawati''' is a [[Rajasthani language]] of [[Indo-Aryan languages]] family and is spoken by about three million speakers in [[Churu]], [[Jhunjhunu]] and [[Sikar]] [[districts of Rajasthan]].<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20160303194604/http://www.sumania.com/lang/allindi10.html Shekhawati]</ref> Though a very important dialect from the grammatical and literary points of view, yet very little work is carried out on it. \nIn 2001 A [[descriptive grammar]] of Shekhawati has been published. Shekhawati, like [[Bagri language|Bagri]] dialect of [[Ganganagar]] and [[Hanumangarh]] districts, has [[parallel lexicon]] which make it very rich from the [[lexicographical]] point of view. [[Word order]] is typical [[Subject\u2013object\u2013verb|SOV]] and there is existence of [[implosives]]. Beside presence of [[high tone]] at [[suprasegmental]] level classify it with other [[dialects of Rajasthani]]. It has contributed a lot to the development of Rajasthani language and [[linguistics]].\n\n==References==\n\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Languages of Rajasthan]]\n\n\n{{IndoAryan-lang-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Paradoctor", "label": "safe", "comment": "dab", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shekhawati_language"}
{"title_page": "HMS Terror (I03)", "text_new": "{{short description|Erebus-class monitor}}\n{{other ships|HMS Terror}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=March 2017}}\n{|{{Infobox ship begin}}\n{{Infobox ship image\n|Ship image=HMS Terror (I03).jpg\n|Ship caption=HMS ''Terror'' underway in [[Plymouth Sound]], October 1933\n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n|Hide header=\n|Ship country=United Kingdom\n|Ship flag={{shipboxflag|UK|naval}}\n|Ship name=''Terror''\n|Ship operator={{navy|UK}}\n|Ship builder=[[Harland & Wolff]], [[Belfast]]\n|Ship yard number=493\n|Ship laid down=26 October 1915\n|Ship launched=18 May 1916\n|Ship completed= 6 August 1916\n|Ship commissioned=22 July 1916\n|Ship refit=\n|Ship motto=\n|Ship nickname=\n|Ship honours=\n|Ship fate=[[Scuttled]] 24 February 1941\n|Ship status=\n|Ship notes=\n|Ship badge=\n}}\n{{Infobox ship characteristics\n|Hide header=\n|Header caption= (as built)\n|Ship class=[[Erebus-class monitor|''Erebus''-class]] [[Monitor (warship)|monitor]]\n|Ship displacement={{convert|8,450|LT|t|lk=on}}\n|Ship length=*{{convert|380|ft|m|abbr=on|1}} ([[Length between perpendiculars|p/p]]) \n*{{convert|405|ft|m|abbr=on|1}} ([[Length overall|o/a]])\n|Ship beam={{convert|88|ft|2|in|m|abbr=on|1}}\n|Ship draught={{convert|11|ft|8|in|m|abbr=on|1}}\n|Ship power=*4 \u00d7 [[Babcock & Wilcox boiler]]s \n*{{convert|6000|ihp|kW|lk=on|abbr=on}}\n|Ship propulsion=2 \u00d7 [[Propeller|screw]]s; 2 \u00d7 [[Triple expansion engine|triple-expansion steam engines]]\n|Ship speed={{convert|12|kn|lk=in}} (service)\n|Ship range={{cvt|2480|nmi|lk=in}}\n|Ship complement=204\n|Ship armament=*1 \u00d7 twin {{convert|15|in|mm|abbr=on|0}} guns\n*1 \u00d7 single {{convert|3|in|mm|abbr=on|0}} [[AA gun]]\n*2 \u00d7 single 12 [[Caliber#Pounds as a measure of cannon bore|pdr]], {{cvt|3|in|mm}} guns\n|Ship armour=*[[Deck (ship)|Deck]]: {{convert|1|to|4|in|mm|abbr=on|0}} \n*[[Bulkhead (partition)|Bulkhead]]s: {{convert|4|in|mm|abbr=on|0}}\n*[[Barbette]]s: {{convert|8|in|mm|abbr=on|0}}\n*[[Gun turret|Turret]]: {{convert|5|to|13|in|mm|abbr=on|0}}\n*[[Conning tower]]: {{convert|6|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}\n|Ship notes=\n}}\n{{Infobox ship characteristics\n|Hide header=\n|Header caption= (1939 refit)\n|Ship armament=*1 \u00d7 twin {{convert|15|in|mm|abbr=on|0}} guns\n*6 \u00d7 single {{convert|4|in|mm|abbr=on|0}} guns\n*2 \u00d7 quadruple {{convert|0.5|in|mm|abbr=on|1}} machine guns\n|Ship notes=\n}}\n|}\n\n'''HMS ''Terror''''' was an [[Erebus class monitor|''Erebus''-class]] [[Monitor (warship)|monitor]] built for the [[Royal Navy]] during the First World War in [[Belfast]], [[Northern Ireland]]. Completed in 1916, she was assigned to the [[Dover Patrol]] where her primary duties involved bombarding German targets on the [[German occupation of Belgium during World War I|Belgian coast]], particularly at the ports of [[Zeebrugge]] and [[Ostend]]. In October 1917 ''Terror'' was hit by three torpedoes, taking severe damage to the bow and had to be towed into [[Portsmouth]] for repair. In April 1918 she participated in the [[Zeebrugge raid]] and provided gunnery support for the [[Fifth Battle of Ypres]] in September of the same year.\n\nAfter the war the monitor was attached to [[HMS Excellent (shore establishment)|HMS ''Excellent'']], the Royal Navy's gunnery school in Portsmouth and participated in gunnery trials in the 1920s. In January 1934 ''Terror'' became the base ship at [[Singapore Naval Base|Sembawang Naval Base]] in [[Singapore in the Straits Settlements|Singapore]] where she remained for the rest of the decade. From May 1939 to the end of the year she underwent an extensive refit in Singapore's dockyards.\n\nFollowing the outbreak of the Second World War and the completion of her refit, ''Terror'' was ordered home to Europe in January 1940. From early March the monitor served in the Mediterranean where she defended [[Siege of Malta (1940)|Malta]] from Italian air raids before supporting the land-based assault of Italian positions in North Africa at the end of the year. In January 1941 the ship assisted with the capture of [[Bardia]] and [[Tobruk]] before she attempted to defend [[Benghazi]] from German air attacks in February. Suffering damage from two air attacks and two mines on 22 and 23 February, ''Terror'' was [[scuttled]] off the coast of [[Italian Libya|Libya]] in the early hours of 24 February. The crew were evacuated to the [[minesweeper]] {{HMS|Fareham|J89|2}} and [[corvette]] {{HMS|Salvia|K97|2}} prior to her sinking.\n\n==Background==\nDuring the First World War, the Royal Navy developed several classes of ships which were designed to give close support to troops ashore through the use of [[Naval Gunfire Support|naval bombardment]].<ref>Crossley 2013 c. 1; Buxton 2008 c. 1</ref> Termed [[Monitor (warship)|monitors]], they owed little to the monitors of the 19th century, though they shared the characteristics of poor seaworthiness, shallow [[Draft (hull)|draught]] and heavy armament in turrets. The size of the various monitor classes of the Royal Navy and their armaments varied greatly. The {{sclass-|Marshal Ney|monitor|4}} was the United Kingdom's first attempt at a monitor carrying {{convert|15|in|mm|abbr=on|0}} guns.<ref>Crossley 2013 c. 2, para. 24</ref> Following construction of the first two of the ''Marshall Ney-class'', another four were ordered in May 1915, with the [[Harland and Wolff]] [[shipyard]] at [[Govan]] receiving a contract to construct two hulls, which were given [[yard number]]s 492 and 493. However, all four were cancelled in June when it was realised that there were insufficient gun turrets to complete both the [[battleship]], {{HMS|Royal Oak|08|2}}, and the monitors before 1917.<ref>Buxton 2008 c. 8.1</ref>\n\nBy August 1915, {{HMS|Marshal Ney||2}}, the first of its class, had revealed a very poor performance in its sea trials. Its engines would not start reliably and were prone to stalling,<ref>Crossley 2013 c. 2, para. 25</ref> making it impossible for the ship to achieve even the minimum standard for the trial of four hours of continuous sailing at full power. The vessel was also difficult to steer.<ref>Buxton 2008 c. 4.2, para. 3</ref> Disappointed by the failure, the [[Admiralty]] began the design of a replacement class on 6 September, which incorporated lessons learned from all of the previous classes of monitor commissioned during the war. Some of the main modifications were an increase in the power supply to guarantee a speed of {{convert|12|kn}} and a change to the angles and lines of the hull to improve steering. Another significant change was to raise the top of the [[anti-torpedo bulge]] above the waterline and reduce its width; both changes would improve the stability and maneuverability of the ship at sea. The bulge was fitted along each side of the ship and was intended to absorb the impact of any explosions. To maintain protection while reducing the bulge's width, its inner compartment was made water tight and filled with 70 steel tubes, rather than leaving the inner compartment open to the sea as in previous designs.<ref name=\"Brown1999p148\">Brown 1999 p. 148</ref><ref name=\"Buxton8.2p2\">Buxton 2008 c. 8.2</ref>\n\n==Design and construction==\nThe new design, which would later be named the ''Erebus''-class, was for a vessel {{convert|405|ft|m|abbr=on|lk=on|1}} long, {{convert|88|ft|2|in|m|abbr=on|1}} [[Beam (nautical)|wide]] with a draught of {{convert|11|ft|8|in|m|abbr=on|1}}. It would have {{convert|8,450|LT|t|lk=on|abbr=on}} [[Displacement (ship)#Loaded displacement|loaded displacement]],<ref name=\"Buxtonc8.3para2\">Buxton 2008 c. 8.3 para. 2</ref>{{efn-lr|Official figures for displacement on completion were not recorded for either vessel of the ''Erebus''-class, leading to historians estimating the true displacement from the completed design and manifest. Buxton suggests a figure of 8,450{{&nbsp}}long tons for [[Displacement (ship)#Loaded displacement|loaded displacement]] at completion.<ref name=\"Buxtonc8.3para2\"/> An alternative figure of {{convert|7,200|LT|t|abbr=on}} was officially recorded for ''Terror's'' 1933 refit, though Buxton reports that this figure appears to be a mistake as it does not align with the ship's recorded loaded displacement for that period.<ref name=\"Buxton8.9\">Buxton 2008 c. 8.9</ref>}} with a maximum operational speed of {{convert|13|kn|lk=on}} produced by [[Triple expansion engine|triple-expansion steam engines]] with two shafts, and a crew of 204. Power would be provided by four [[Water-tube boiler#Babcock & Wilcox boiler|Babcock & Wilcox water-tube boilers]], which would generate a combined {{convert|6000|ihp|kW|lk=on|abbr=on}}. The monitors would have an operational range of {{cvt|2480|nmi|lk=in}} at a speed of 12{{&nbsp}}knots.<ref name=\"Buxton8.9\"/> \n\nThe ships would be armoured to a similar standard to the {{sclass-|Abercrombie|monitor|4}}, which were launched in April 1915.<ref name=\"Buxton8.9\"/> Deck armour would range from {{convert|1|in|mm|abbr=on|0}} on the [[forecastle]], through {{convert|2|in|mm|abbr=on|0}} on the upper deck and {{convert|4|in|mm|abbr=on|0}} over the [[Magazine (artillery)|magazine]] and [[Belt armor|belt]].<ref name=\"Buxton8.2p4\">Buxton 2008 c. 8.2, para. 4</ref> With the main 15 in guns being originally intended for use on a battleship, the armour for the [[Gun turret|turret]] was substantially thicker than elsewhere in the design; with {{convert|13|in|mm|abbr=on|0}} on the front, {{convert|11|in|mm|abbr=on|0}} on the other sides and {{convert|5|in|mm|abbr=on|0}} on the roof.<ref name=\"Buxton8.2p4\"/><ref name=\"Buxton8.9\"/> The main gun's [[barbette]] would be protected by {{convert|8|in|mm|abbr=on|0}} of armour.<ref name=\"Buxton2.2\">Buxton 2008 c. 2.2, para. 1</ref> The [[conning tower]] was protected by {{convert|6|in|mm|abbr=on|0}} of armour on the sides and {{convert|2.5|in|mm|abbr=on|0}} on the roof.<ref>Buxton 2008 c. 2.11</ref> Each anti-torpedo bulge was {{convert|13|ft|abbr=on|0}} wide with an outer air-filled compartment {{convert|9|ft|abbr=on}} wide and an inner compartment {{convert|4|ft|abbr=on}} wide containing the steel tubes.<ref name=\"Buxton8.2p2\"/>\n\nOrders for two vessels of the new design were placed with Harland and Wolff on 29 September with reinstated yard numbers 492 and 493, which were renamed respectively {{HMS|Erebus|I02|2}} and ''Terror'' on 13 October. ''Terror'' was [[laid down]] at Harland and Wolff's shipyard in Belfast, Northern Ireland on 26 October 1915 and [[Ceremonial ship launching|launched]] on 18 May 1916.<ref name=\"BelfastConstruct\">Buxton 2008 c. 8.3</ref>\n\nThe ship's main armament consisted of two [[BL 15 inch Mk I naval gun|BL 15{{&nbsp}}in Mk I naval guns]] in a single forward [[Gun turret|turret]]. ''Terror's'' turret had belonged to ''Marshal Ney'', which had been rearmed with smaller guns following its poor sea trials.<ref>Crossley 2013 c. 2, para. 29</ref>{{efn-lr|There is some confusion in the sources as to the fate of ''Marshall Ney's'' turret. Jane's Fighting Ships (1919) states that it was fitted to ''Erebus''.<ref name=\"Janes1919\">Parkes & Prendergast 1919 p. 90</ref> However Buxton (2008) and Crossley (2013) both agree that ''Ney's'' turret was fitted to ''Terror'' in Belfast while ''Erebus'' received at [[Clydebank]] a gun originally intended as a spare for {{HMS|Furious|47|2}}.}} Learning from the earlier experience with ''Ney'', the turrets were adjusted to increase elevation to 30 degrees, which would add greater firing range.<ref name=\"BelfastConstruct\"/> Unlike her sister, ''Terror'' was launched with a minimal secondary armament of one {{convert|3|in|mm|abbr=on|0}} [[Anti-aircraft warfare|anti-aircraft]] gun and two 12 [[Caliber#Pounds as a measure of cannon bore|pdr]], {{cvt|3|in|mm}} guns, which fired projectiles weighing {{convert|12.5|lb|kg|lk=on}}.{{efn-lr|Sources are unclear on the type of 12{{&nbsp}}pdr guns installed on ''Terror'', but two models commonly used by the Royal Navy at the time were the [[QF 12-pounder 12 cwt naval gun|QF 12{{&nbsp}}pdr, 12 cwt]] and [[QF 12-pounder 18 cwt naval gun|QF 12{{&nbsp}}pdr, 18 cwt]] naval guns.}}<ref name=\"Buxtonc8.8para1\">Buxton 2008 c. 8.8, para. 1</ref><ref name=\"Janes1919\"/>\n\n''Terror'' was [[Ship commissioning|commissioned]] on 22 July 1916 before conducting [[sea trial]]s, during which the ship was slower than her sister at {{convert|13.1|kn}} compared to {{convert|14.1|kn}} for ''Erebus''. However, under service conditions the maximum speed that could be achieved for both vessels was 13{{&nbsp}}knots with a clean hull or 12{{&nbsp}}knots with a [[Fouling|fouled]] hull. ''Terror'' was recorded as officially completed on 6 August.<ref>Buxton 2008 c. 8.3, para. 3 & c. 8.9</ref>\n\n===Modifications===\nWithin a few months of launch, ''Terror's'' armament was supplemented by two [[QF 6-inch naval gun|QF 6{{&nbsp}}in naval guns]] with a second 3{{&nbsp}}in gun following soon after. Additional guns were fitted while her bow was being repaired from October 1917; two more 6{{&nbsp}}in guns and two [[QF 2-pounder naval gun|2 pdr, {{cvt|1.6|in|mm}} pom-poms]], which fired projectiles weighing {{convert|2|lb|kg}}. In the summer of 1918 the 6{{&nbsp}}in guns were replaced with eight [[BL 4-inch Mk IX naval gun|BL 4{{&nbsp}}in Mk IX naval guns]].<ref name=\"Buxtonc8.8para1\"/><ref name=\"Janes1919\"/> The monitor's armaments were modified temporarily during the early 1920's while the ship took part in gunnery trials to test new types of shells and armour.<ref name=\"Buxton2008c8.5\">Buxton 2008 c. 8.5, para. 9-10</ref>\n\nThe 12{{&nbsp}}pdr and 2{{&nbsp}}pdr guns were removed during ''Terror's'' 1933 refit while the ship's capacity for oil and ammunition reserves were increased for her journey to [[Singapore in the Straits Settlements|Singapore]]. During ''Terror's'' 1939 refit her eight 4{{&nbsp}}in guns were replaced with six [[QF 4-inch naval gun Mk V|QF 4{{&nbsp}}in Mk V naval guns]] and the 3{{&nbsp}}in anti-aircraft guns were replaced by eight [[Vickers .50 machine gun|Vickers {{convert|0.5|in|mm|abbr=on|1}} machine guns]] in two quadruple mounts. At Malta in 1940 the monitor had a further refit to increase her deck armour.<ref>Buxton 2008 c. 8.8, para. 3</ref>\n\n==Service history==\n\n===First World War===\n\n[[File:HMS Terror 15 inch guns 1915 IWM SP 1612.jpg|thumb|left|The turret and main armament of ''Terror'', 1915]] On completion, ''Terror'' immediately departed Belfast and joined the [[Dover Patrol]] on 8 August.<ref>Prince 2012 p. 36</ref> In August and September she joined with other members of the patrol to bombard minor targets in occupied Belgium. However, the new monitor only fired a small number of shots, as it was felt wiser to conserve her guns for more important targets. On 24 September the ship made an attempt to bombard the port of [[Zeebrugge]] but this was soon aborted when the weather conditions prevented the accurate observation of [[Indirect fire|fall of shot]] and any subsequent correction of trajectory. Poor weather conditions continued for the rest of 1916 and the patrol made no further attempts that year to bombard the Belgian coast. During the winter of 1916 and 1917, ''Terror'' acted as a guard boat for ships anchored at [[The Downs (ship anchorage)|The Downs]], following a spate of attacks by German destroyers.<ref name=\"Buxton8.4\">Buxton 2008 Chapter 8.4</ref>\n\nIn early 1917, ''Terror'' and the rest of the patrol made several aborted attempts to bombard the [[lock gate]]s of the Bruges Canal at Zeebrugge but the operation had to be postponed each time. Reasons for postponement included snapped towlines and poor weather conditions. However, the operation eventually commenced on the evening of 11 May with ''Terror'' acting as flagship for Vice-Admiral [[Reginald Bacon]]. The flotilla anchored off Zeebrugge and began their bombardment at around 05:00 on 12 May, with the monitors {{HMS|Marshal Soult||2}} and ''Terror'' concentrating on the south lock gate and her sister ship ''Erebus'' concentrating on the north gate. Poor visibility and problems with [[Air Observation Post|spotting aircraft]] meant that the fall of shot couldn't be fully observed or their trajectories corrected. The German shore battery began to return fire but ceased after four rounds due to the same poor visibility, enhanced by a British [[smoke screen]]. The British bombardment was called off at 06:00 due to a change in the wind direction clearing their smoke screen and making their ships visible from the shore. The flotilla withdrew to Dover, in the mistaken belief that their bombardment had been successful. Subsequent aerial reconnaissance revealed damage to the surrounding area but the lock gates, the primary targets, were untouched.<ref>Buxton 2008 Chapter 4.3</ref><ref>Dunn, Chapter 14, Section: \"The bombardment of Zeebrugge, 12 May 1917\"</ref>\n\nA bombardment of [[Ostend]] on 5 June by ''Erebus'' and ''Terror'' was more successful, destroying or damaging several vessels and damaging the dockyard.<ref>Dunn 2017 chapter 17, section \"The bombardment of Ostend, 5 June 1957\"</ref>{{efn-lr|Crossley (2013) makes the claim that [[SM UC-70|U-boat UC.70]] was destroyed in the 5 June attack. However, Dunn (2017) observes that UC.70 was not destroyed until 1918 and he can find no corresponding record of a U-boat being destroyed on that day. Buxton (2008) clarifies that the U-boat was sunk in the attack but subsequently refloated and repaired.<ref name=\"Buxton8.4\"/>}} However, the [[Dry dock#Floating|floating dock]]s were not affected until a subsequent bombardment by ''Terror'' on 22 September caused severe damage to both the dockyard and the floating docks.<ref name=\"Crossley2013c5\">Crossley 2013 Chapter 5</ref>\n\nOn 19 October, in an encounter with three [[A-class torpedo boat|German motor torpedo boats]] (''A59'', ''A60'' and ''A61'')<ref name=\"Buxton8.4\"/> off Dunkirk, ''Terror'' was hit by three {{convert|17.7|inch|mm|abbr=on}} torpedoes. Two impacted on the right forward, creating a {{convert|50|ft|m|abbr=on}} long hole in the bow, while the other hit the anti-torpedo bulge further aft, which absorbed the damage.<ref name=\"Brown1999p148\"/>{{efn-lr|Brown, D. K. credits the anti-torpedo bulges as being responsible for protecting ''Terror'' from more severe damage to the main hull.<ref>Brown 1999 p. 164</ref> However, Crossly observes that the bulges only protected the ship from the hit further aft and it was the watertight doors that saved the ship by restricting flood water to the forward compartments only.<ref name=\"Crossley2013c5\"/>}} There were no casualties and the ship was beached before being refloated and towed into Dunkirk harbour for temporary repairs. Captain Bruton was advised by a salvage expert to sail the ship stern-first to Portsmouth to reduce pressure on the bow but chose to disregard the advice. The ship sailed first to Dover on 21 October but on the next leg of the journey to Portsmouth two days later, in heavy seas, a major leak developed off [[Hastings]]. The crew evacuated while a tug boat maintained a line to the ship. They were able to reboard ''Terror'' the next day and brought her back into Dover harbour. During the second attempt to reach Portsmouth on 27 October, Bruton again refused to sail the ship backwards but changed his mind after the salvage expert left the ship. She was then towed backwards to Portsmouth, where it took until early January to repair the damage.<ref>Dunn, Chapter 13, Section: \"New monitors\"</ref>  A [[Court-martial|Court of Inquiry]] was called into the 23 October abandonment. Bacon supported Bruton's decision to leave the vessel and the salvage expert was not called to give evidence. The inquiry absolved Bruton and his officers of any blame over the incident.<ref name=\"Buxton8.4\"/>\n\n[[File:The Guns. HMS Terror, 1918 Art.IWMART1379.jpg|thumb|A painting by [[John Lavery]] of ''Terror's'' guns at Dover in 1918]]\nOn the morning of 21 March 1918 she helped foil a German raid on [[Dunkirk]] by nine destroyers and ten torpedo boats, which had been intended to support the [[Spring Offensive]]. Two of the torpedo boats were destroyed by the [[flotilla leader]] ''[[Faulknor-class flotilla leader|Botha]]'' and the rest withdrew to Ostend under a smoke screen.<ref>Dunn 2017 chapter 17, section \"HMS Botha, 21 March 1918\"</ref> On the evening of 22 March ''Terror'' bombarded Ostend harbour, firing 39 shots before a German smoke screen obscured the harbour from view. Aerial photographs taken the next day revealed that all 39 shots had landed within the target area.<ref>Lake 2002 Chapter 6</ref> In April, ''Terror'' was in the Long Range Bombardment force for the [[Zeebrugge raid]] with ''Erebus'' and destroyers ''[[Talisman-class destroyer|Termagant]]'', [[Yarrow Later M class destroyer|''Truculent'']], and [[Yarrow M class destroyer|''Manley'']].<ref>Warner 1978 Section: \"Vessels taking part.\"</ref> \n\nIn September, in preparation for a further offensive, ''Terror'' had her 15{{&nbsp}}in gun barrels replaced. Having fired around 340 rounds, it was felt they had become worn and were in no condition to support a prolonged battle.<ref name=\"Buxton8.4\"/> On 27 September, ''Terror'' and ''Erebus'' provided gunnery support for the [[Fifth Battle of Ypres]]; their objective being to bombard positions around Zeebrugge and Ostend, with the aim of diverting German attention from other fronts.<ref name=\"Crossley2013c5\"/>\n\n===Inter-war years===\nAfter the war ''Terror'' was attached to [[HMS Excellent (shore establishment)|HMS ''Excellent'']], the Royal Navy gunnery school at Portsmouth, from January 1919 until at least December 1920.<ref>{{cite book |date=January 1919 |title=Supplement to the Monthly Navy List Showing Organisation of the Fleet, Flag Officers' Commands; Corrected to 1st January 1919 |url=https://archive.org/details/navylistjan1919grea |location=London |publisher=[[His Majesty's Stationery Office]] |page=[https://archive.org/details/navylistjan1919grea/page/16 16] |access-date=1 September 2018 }}</ref><ref>{{cite book |date=January 1921 |title=The Navy List for January 1921, Corrected to the 18 December 1920 |url=https://archive.org/details/navylistjan1921grea |location=London |publisher=[[His Majesty's Stationery Office]] |page=[https://archive.org/details/navylistjan1921grea/page/704 704] |access-date=28 August 2018 }}</ref>\n\nIn 1919 and the early 1920s, she was used for gunnery trials against several old warships including {{SMS|Baden}} and {{HMS|Superb|1907|6}}. This included the test firing of over thirty new types of 15{{&nbsp}}in shells in 1921 and testing the amount of damage caused to new types of armour plating in 1922.<ref>Brown 2000 p. 19</ref><ref>Buxton 2008 c. 8.5, para. 5-7</ref> For many of these trials ''Terror'' was temporarily fitted with new guns of varying sizes, including a [[BL 6-inch Mk XII naval gun|BL 6{{&nbsp}}in Mk XII naval gun]]. From May 1924 until 1933 the monitor was again attached to ''Excellent'', this time in the role of [[Training ship|Turret Drill Ship]].<ref name=\"Buxton2008c8.5\"/>\n\nAs a result of increased tensions in the [[Pacific Ocean]], following Japan's withdrawal from the [[League of Nations]], ''Terror'' was overhauled and recommissioned with new armaments before being dispatched to Singapore in 1933. Her role was to assist in the development of the [[Singapore Naval Base|Sembawang Naval Base]] and act initially as a moored battery until the base's own 15{{&nbsp}}in guns were completed.<ref>Murfett 2011 p.165</ref><ref>Clements 2016 p. 113</ref> \n\nShe departed Plymouth on 9 October 1933, in company with the {{sic|hide=y|salvage|d}} trawler ''Fastnet'' and the barrage vessel ''Sandgate'',<ref name=\"Buxton2008c8.5\"/>{{efn-lr|''Fastnet'' was a former fishing vessel that was abandoned after crashing into the rocks off Iceland. It was sold to the Royal Navy as scrap but refloated and put to a useful purpose. ''Sandgate'' was a barrage vessel, designed and launched without an engine in 1917; it would require to be towed in order to move locations.}} to begin the journey to the Far East. Never designed for such an arduous journey the ships struggled with storms in the [[Atlantic Ocean|Atlantic]] and [[Mediterranean Sea|Mediterranean]]. The ''Fastnet'' was damaged twice during the voyage, spending three weeks in the dockyard at [[Gibraltar]] and receiving a temporary patch at [[Sabang, Indonesia|Sabang]] in [[Sumatra]] to allow it to limp the short distance to Singapore. ''Terror'' also had an adventure while passing through the [[Suez Canal]]; a tow rope was cast off too soon, causing the ship to swing broadside across the channel with the bow and stern touching either bank. However, no damage was caused and she was quickly refloated to resume her journey.<ref name=\"FastnetJan34\">{{cite news |date=26 January 1934 |title=Naval Curiosities At Singapore; The Terror and the Fastnet |work=The Singapore Free Press and Mercantile Advertiser |language=English |location=Singapore |page= 3 |url=https://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article/singfreepressb19340126-1.2.24 |accessdate=22 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n''Terror'' arrived at Singapore on the evening of 14 January 1934 along with the [[heavy cruiser]] {{HMS|Kent|54|2}}, flagship of the [[China Station]], destroyers {{HMS|Veteran|D72|2}} and {{HMS|Wren|1919|2}} and the [[aircraft carrier]] {{HMS|Eagle|1918|2}}.<ref>{{cite news |date=15 January 1934 |title=Admiral Dreyer |work=The Straits Times |language=English |location=Singapore |page= 11 |url=https://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article/straitstimes19340115-1.2.53 |accessdate=22 December 2019}}</ref> A local paper described the monitor's journey from England with ''Fastnet'' as a \"waddle,\" pointing out that two destroyers had passed them at Gibraltar and arrived in Singapore in November.<ref name=\"FastnetJan34\"/>\n\nIn May 1935, to celebrate the [[silver jubilee]] of [[George V|King George V]], ''Terror'' opened itself to the public of Singapore to host a charity ball.<ref>{{cite news |date=6 March 1935 |title=Jubilee Ball On Terror |work=The Singapore Free Press and Mercantile Advertiser |language=English |location=Singapore |page= 7 |url=https://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article/singfreepressb19350306-1.2.58 |accessdate=22 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 1937 she participated in gunnery trials alongside Singapore's newly completed 15{{&nbsp}}in guns, in order to develop the shore defences' capabilities with [[indirect fire]]. Both ''Terror'' and the shore batteries practised against a target towed at high speed by the heavy cruiser {{HMS|Berwick|65|2}}.<ref name=\"Buxton2008c8.5\"/> \n\nIn January and March 1939 ''Terror'' participated in live fire drills off the coast of Singapore,<ref>{{cite news |date=3 January 1939 |title=Firing practice for monitor Terror |work=The Straits Times |language=English |location=Singapore |page= 15 |url=https://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article/straitstimes19390103-1.2.95 |accessdate=22 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |date=7 March 1939 |title=H.M.S. Terror gun practice |work=The Straits Times |language=English |location=Singapore |page= 12 |url=https://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article/straitstimes19390307-1.2.67 |accessdate=22 December 2019}}</ref> before entering drydock in May for an extensive refit.<ref>{{cite news |date=23 May 1939 |title=Terror undergoing refit |work=The Singapore Free Press and Mercantile Advertiser |language=English |location=Singapore |page= 3 |url=https://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article/singfreepressb19390523-1.2.34 |accessdate=22 December 2019}}</ref> She was fitted with six high-angle anti-aircraft guns and her ageing 15{{&nbsp}}in gun barrels were replaced by partly worn barrels from the [[super-dreadnought battleship]] {{HMS|Revenge|06|2}}.<ref name=\"Crossley2013c7\">Crossley 2013 Chapter 7</ref>\n\nIn May 1939 the [[Colonial Office]] suggested moving ''Terror'' to the [[West Indies]] in order to protect the oil fields of [[Trinidad]] from growing internal threats, such as an [[British West Indian labour unrest of 1934\u201339|emboldened labour movement]] and anti-colonial sentiment in the region. However, the [[Admiralty]] declined the request, as a floating battery would not be able to offer the required protection and would itself be at considerable risk of submarine attack. They instead ordered a review of Trinidad's naval defence requirements.<ref>Spence 2015 p. 30</ref> Alternative postings for ''Terror'' at [[Aden Protectorate|Aden]] or [[Trincomalee]] were also considered.<ref name=\"Buxton2008c86-1\">Buxton 2008 c. 8.6, para. 1-2</ref>\n\n===Second World War===\nAt the outbreak of war on 3 September 1939, ''Terror'' was continuing her refit at Singapore, under the command of Commander Henry John Haynes.<ref>{{cite book |date=September 1939 |title=The Navy List for September 1939, Corrected to 18 August 1939 |url=https://archive.org/details/navylistsep1939grea |location=London |publisher=[[His Majesty's Stationery Office]] |pages=[https://archive.org/details/navylistsep1939grea/page/247 247], 337 |access-date=1 September 2018 }}</ref><ref name=\"Crossley2013c7\"/> She received orders to return to the [[English Channel]] in November but didn't depart Singapore until 29 January 1940, after completing her long refit. The monitor arrived at Suez in early March where her orders were changed to attach the ship to the depleted [[Mediterranean fleet]].<ref name=\"Buxton2008c86-1\"/> \n\nAt the end of the month she left the Royal Navy base at [[Alexandria]] to lend the strength of her guns to [[Malta]], which the British felt was vulnerable to an expected Italian attack. In particular, ''Terror's'' 15{{&nbsp}}in main guns were far superior to the island's [[BL 9.2-inch Mk IX \u2013 X naval gun|{{convert|9.2|inch|mm|abbr=on}} guns]].<ref name=\"Crossley2013c7\"/> Arriving at Malta on 4 April, she was present for the Italian declaration of war on 10 June and the first air attacks on the island by the ''[[Regia Aeronautica]]'', beginning just before 7 am on 11 June.<ref name=\"Buxton2008c86-1\"/><ref>Jacobs 2016 pp. 13\u201315</ref> In the first day alone the island was hit by 9 separate air raids and an estimated 83 in the first month.<ref>Thomas 1999 p. 22</ref> For three months the monitor helped to [[Siege of Malta (1940)|defend Malta]] from daily air attacks until the arrival of additional anti-aircraft guns allowed a refit of her armour to begin on 4 September.<ref name=\"Buxton2008c86-1\"/>\n\nOn 9 November ''Terror'' sailed from Malta to the Royal Navy's refuelling base at [[Souda Bay]] in [[Crete]] to again provide anti-aircraft support.<ref name=\"LindPayne6263\">Lind & Payne 1976 pp. 62\u201363</ref><ref name=\"Crossley2013c7\"/> She was stationed in the bay on 3 December when two Italian aircraft dropped torpedoes into the harbour, one of which hit and badly damaged the stern of the [[light cruiser]] {{HMS|Glasgow|C21|2}}.<ref>Otter 2001 Chapter 7</ref>\n\n[[File:WesternDesertBattle Area1941 en.svg|thumb|{{centre|Area of operations December 1940 to February 1941 (click to enlarge)}}]]\n''Terror'' later moved to North Africa where she supported [[Operation Compass]], the British assault against the [[Tenth Army (Italy)|Italian Tenth Army]] in [[Italian Libya|Libya]]. The monitor shelled Italian positions at Maktila in Egypt on the night of 8 December, as part of the [[Battle of Sidi Barrani]], before coming under the command of Captain [[Hector Waller]]'s Inshore Squadron off Libya on 13 December.<ref>Brown 2013 p.33; Latimer 2013</ref><ref name=\"LindPayne6263\"/> During the successful advance by the [[Western Desert Force]] ''Terror'' bombarded Italian land forces and fortifications, amongst others the fortified port of [[Bardia]] in eastern Libya on 16 December.<ref>Lind & Payne 1976 pp. 63\u201365</ref> After the Bardia bombardment concern was raised about the condition of the 15{{&nbsp}}in gun barrels which had been fitted, having been previously used, in 1939. The barrels were inspected by [[Andrew Cunningham, 1st Viscount Cunningham of Hyndhope|Vice Admiral Cunningham]] and the order was given for ''Terror'' to reduce the amount of [[cordite]] used when firing the main guns, in an attempt to extend the weapons' useful life.<ref name=\"Crossley2013c7\"/>\n\nIn a further attempt to conserve the monitor's main guns, her duties were changed to concentrate on providing anti-aircraft cover for the rest of the squadron and to ferry supplies from Alexandria.<ref name=\"Buxton2008c86-5\">Buxton 2008 c. 8.6, para. 5-7</ref> The ship also served as a water carrier for the advancing British and Commonwealth army.<ref>Latimer 2013</ref>\n\nOn the morning of 3 January 1941, she participated in a [[Battle of Bardia|major bombardment of Bardia]] together with a number of battleships and their destroyer escorts. The formation was protected by a screen of fighters; [[No. 274 Squadron RAF]] intercepted five Italian [[Savoia-Marchetti SM.79]] bombers that were attacking ''Terror'' nine miles to the north east of Bardia. Three of the bombers were shot down or crashed and a fourth was damaged.<ref>Wynn 2015 p. 2034</ref> The battleships, the destroyers and their fighter cover were withdrawn in the afternoon leaving the monitor to continue the bombardment with the [[gunboat]]s [[HMS Aphis|''Aphis'']] and [[HMS Ladybird (1916)|''Ladybird'']]. Bardia was captured the following day.<ref>Lind & Payne 1976 pp. 64\u201365</ref>\n\nAlong with the flotilla leader [[HMAS Stuart (D00)|''Stuart'']], gunboat [[HMS Gnat (T60)|''Gnat'']] and destroyers [[HMAS Vampire (D68)|''Vampire'']] and [[HMAS Voyager (D31)|''Voyager'']], ''Terror'' supported the [[6th Division (Australia)|6th Australian Division's]] assault on [[Tobruk]] on 21 January with the port being secured on 22nd.<ref>Lind & Payne 1976 p. 65</ref> By this point the monitor's main gun barrels had each fired over 600 rounds of ammunition and the [[rifling]] had been worn away. While the main guns could still be fired, the shots would rarely land accurately and frequently exploded in mid-air.<ref name=\"Buxton2008c86-5\"/> ''Terror'' was now relegated solely to the role of a mobile anti-aircraft platform and her armaments were supplemented by eight {{convert|20|mm|in|abbr=on}} anti-aircraft guns that had been captured from the Italians.<ref name=\"Crossley2013c7\"/>{{efn-lr|The Italian army at the time used two models of 20{{&nbsp}}mm anti-aircraft guns; the [[Breda Model 35]] and the [[Cannone-Mitragliera da 20/77 (Scotti)|20{{&nbsp}}mm Scotti]]. It is unclear which model was installed on ''Terror'' or if a mixture of the two was used.}}\n\nIn early February the British and Commonwealth forces captured the port of [[Benghazi]] from the Italians in the [[Battle of Beda Fomm]]. Intending to use the port as a key supply point for their armies, the allies recognised that the shortage of anti-aircraft guns, lack of radar and limited air cover from the RAF was a strategic weakness that would have to be addressed. However, the capture of the port coincided with the arrival of the [[Luftwaffe]] in North Africa as the advance forces of [[Operation Sonnenblume]]. The Germans immediately began an intense series of air raids against both Benghazi and Tobruk, which included the dropping of [[magnetic mines]] into the harbours.<ref>Raugh 2013 p. 123; Playfair 1956 p. 12</ref> \n\n[[File:Pictures For Illustrating Ritchie Ii Book. November and December 1942, Alexandria, Pictures of Paintings by Lieutenant Commander R Langmaid, Rn, Official Fleet Artist. These Pictures Are For Illustrating a Nava A13648.jpg|thumb|A painting by [[Rowland Langmaid]] of ''Terror's'' last fight.|left]]\nThe minesweeper {{HMS|Peony|K40|2}} cleared a safe channel into Benghazi harbour before the arrival of ''Terror'' on 17 February and a supply convoy the day after.<ref>Brown 2013 p. 63</ref> While ''Peony'' made steady progress in clearing the harbour, work was slow due to the shallow waters reducing the effectiveness of her degaussing equipment. As part of this work, a team from ''Peony'' safely detonated a mine close to ''Terror's'' mooring.<ref>Parker 2013 p. 215</ref> Despite the monitor's efforts to protect the harbour using her anti-aircraft guns, the convoy was unable to offload the majority of its cargo due to the frequent air attacks and sailed on to Tobruk on 20 February. ''Terror'' remained in port together with the minesweeper ''Fareham'' and corvette ''Salvia'' to protect the naval parties clearing the harbour.<ref>Bechthold 2017 pp. 128\u2013129; Playfair 1956 p. 12; Brown 2013 p. 64</ref> \n\n''Terror'' was subjected to continued bombing attacks while in harbour and a near miss early on 22 February caused significant damage and flooding of the decks. Haynes protested the lack of air support to Cunningham along with the dangers of remaining at anchor, stating that it was only a matter of time before ''Terror'' received a direct hit. Accepting this assessment, Cunningham ordered the ship to sail for Tobruk on the evening tide with ''Fareham'' and ''Salvia''.<ref>Brown 2013 p. 64</ref> As they were exiting the harbour the monitor triggered two magnetic mines in the previously cleared channel; although again not a direct hit, the explosions in close proximity caused further damage and flooding.<ref>Bechthold 2017 p. 129</ref> On the evening of 23 February she was attacked once more by German [[Junkers Ju 87]] ''Stuka'' dive-bombers from III/[[StG 2]] under the command of [[Helmut Mahlke]]. The ''gruppe'', which had been initially set up as an anti-shipping unit by the [[Kriegsmarine]], had been drafted in to attack shipping in the vicinity.<ref>Smith 2011, pp. 267\u2013268</ref> The attack occurred while the ship was {{convert|90|miles|km}} from Tobruk; the near misses of this final assault leaving the ship critically damaged. Further floodwater disabled the electric generators and pumps and extinguished the boiler furnaces. The majority of the crew were evacuated to ''Fareham'' and ''Salvia'' with a skeleton crew of officers and anti-aircraft gunners remaining on board to operate the ship. ''Terror'' was taken under tow by ''Fareham'' in an attempt to reach Tobruk and additional ships were scrambled from Alexandria and Tobruk. However, the monitor continued to take on water and it was accepted that she would never reach port. ''Terror'' was [[scuttled]] through the opening of the [[seacock]]s and the use of [[depth charges]] on the morning of 24 February, {{convert|25|miles|km}} to the north west of [[Derna, Libya|Derna]]. The remaining crew were evacuated successfully.<ref>Bechthold 2017 p. 129; Brown 2013 p. 64; Crossley 2013 c. 7, para. 8</ref>{{efn-lr|Bechthold (2017) gives the date of the sinking as 26 February, however Brown (2013), Crossley (2013) and Buxton (2008) agree that her final damage was taken on the evening of 23 February and she was scuttled during the night. Buxton gives 04:20 on 24 February as the precise time of her sinking.}}\n\nFollowing the sinking, Commander Haynes was awarded the [[Distinguished Service Order]] in August 1941 for \"courage, skill and devotion to duty in operations off the Libyan Coast.\" A number of her other officers and crew were awarded the [[Distinguished Service Cross (United Kingdom)|Distinguished Service Cross]], [[Distinguished Service Medal (United Kingdom)|Distinguished Service Medal]] or [[mentioned in dispatches]] for the same reason.<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=35248 |date=15 August 1941 |supp=1 |pages=4781\u20134782 }}</ref>\n\n==Footnotes==\n{{notelist-lr|30em}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n{{refbegin|30em}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Bechthold |first1=Michael |year=2017 |title=Flying to victory: Raymond Collishaw and the western desert campaign, 1940\u20131941 |location=Norman |publisher=University of Oklahoma Press |isbn=9780806157863 }}\n*{{cite book |last1=Brown |first1=David K. |year=2012 |orig-year=1999 |title=The Grand Fleet; Warship Design and Development 1906-1922 |location=Barnsley, UK |publisher=Seaforth Publishing |isbn=9781848320857 }}\n*{{cite book |last1=Brown |first1=David K. |year=2012 |orig-year=2000 |title=Nelson to Vanguard; Warship Design and Development 1923-1945 |location=Barnsley, UK |publisher=Seaforth Publishing |isbn=9781848321496 }}\n*{{cite book |last1=Brown |first1=David |year=2013 |title=Royal Navy and the Mediterranean: Vol. II: November 1940 \u2013 December 1941 |location=Hoboken |publisher=Taylor and Francis |isbn=9781136341205 }}\n*{{cite book |last1=Buxton |first1=Ian |title=Big gun monitors: design, construction and operations 1914-1945 |location=Barnsley, UK |publisher=Pen & Sword |date=2008 |orig-year=1978 |edition=2nd Revised |isbn=978-1-84415-719-8 }}\n*{{cite book |last1=Clements |first1=Bill |title=The Fatal Fortress: The Guns and Fortifications of Singapore 1819 - 1953 |publisher=Pen & Sword |publication-date=2016 |isbn=9781473829619 }}\n*{{cite book |last1=Crossley |first1=Jim |title=Monitors of the Royal Navy; How the fleet brought the great guns to bear |location=Barnsley, UK |publisher=Pen & Sword |year=2013 |isbn=9781783830046 }}\n*{{cite book |last1=Dunn |first1=Steve R |title=Securing the Narrow Sea; The Dover Patrol 1914-1918 |location=Barnsley, UK |publisher=Seaforth Publishing |year=2017 |isbn=9781848322516 }}\n*{{cite book |last1=Jacobs |first1=Peter |year=2016 |title=Fortress Island Malta: Defence & re-supply during the siege |location=Barnsley, UK |publisher=Pen and Sword |isbn=9781473882560 }}\n*{{cite book |last1=Lake |first1=Deborah |title=The Zeebrugge and Ostend Raids 1918 |location=Barnsley, UK |publisher=Leo Cooper |year=2002 |isbn=0850528704 }}\n*{{cite book |last1=